## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of governance in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Governance is the bounded structure
through which decision authority,
review authority,
oversight,
accountability,
and formal control
become meaningful.

Governance is not identical to policy text.
It is the active system of who decides,
who reviews,
who supervises,
and how responsibility is distributed.

## architectural_position
Governance sits between:
- identity and permission
- nation/company/organization authority
- policy application
- security boundary
- audit and escalation handling

## required_behavior
- governance context must remain explicit
- decision and review roles must remain explicit
- accountability chain must remain explicit
- current and historical governance states must remain distinguishable

## canonical_rules
- execution authority must not masquerade as review authority
- oversight must remain attributable
- historical governance trace must remain queryable
- ambiguous governance scope fails closed

## state_model
The governance domain distinguishes:
- proposed governance arrangement
- active governance arrangement
- restricted governance arrangement
- escalated governance state
- historical governance state

## actor_boundary
- decision maker
- reviewer
- overseer
- operator
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if governance context is unclear, stop governance-sensitive action
- if decision/review separation is unclear, fail closed
- if accountability chain is broken, route to escalation
- if governance becomes historical, preserve trace

## review_checklist
- governance context is explicit
- decision/review split is explicit
- accountability chain is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
